  "prompt": "Is the scheme of money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This practice is a criminal offense and is punishable by law.\n\nLaws against money laundering are designed to prevent criminals from disguising the origins of funds obtained through illegal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and terrorism. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nIn addition to domestic laws, many countries have established international agreements and organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), to combat money laundering on a global scale. Financial institutions and businesses are also required to implement measures to detect and report suspicious activities that may be indicative of money laundering.",
